					<h2>Spring is Here</h2>
					<p><img src="/images/125.jpg" alt="Sealions while Whale Watching in Monterey Bay California with Stagnaro Charters"></p>
					<p>Spring is here and so are humpback whale arriving for their feeding season in Monterey Bay. Gray whales continue their northbound migration through our local waters, and dolphin &amp; otter babies are learning to keep up with their folks. Here is what we've seen lately in Monterey Bay.</p>
					<p><img src="/images/126.jpg" alt="Humpback Fluke while Whale Watching in Monterey Bay California with Stagnaro Charters"></p>
					<p>Humpback fluke 3/23/16 Monterey Bay, March 2016</p>
					<p>Wednesday 3/23/16 we saw Gray Whales, Humpback Whales, Dolphins (mamas and babies) and our favorite California Sea Otters!</p>
					<p><img src="/images/127.jpg" alt="Gray Whale while Whale Watching in Monterey Bay California with Stagnaro Charters"></p>
					<p>Gray whale, Spring migration, Monterey Bay, 3/23/16. photo Michael Nelson</p>
					<p>3/20/16 For Sunday's trip, the best report came from one of our passengers, who wrote, "We had clear skies, a smooth trip, and good sightings. There was a small group of about 20 common dolphins porpoising. We then saw a yearling humpback surfacing then diving to feed near the canyon. Later, we came upon another young humpback."</p>
					<p>Saturday 3/19 we saw 500 common dolphins, 3 humpback whales â€” close drive-bys, lots of flukes, plus otters!</p>
					<p>And on Thursday 3/18 we saw otters, lots of dolphins and 6 humpback whales out in Monterey Bay. One of the whales was lunge feeding. Lovely!</p>
